12:00.610 --> 12:04.132
♪ For it won't be long ♪

12:04.157 --> 12:06.952
♪ Till I'm gonna need ♪

12:06.977 --> 12:13.938
♪ Somebody to lean on ♪

12:14.391 --> 12:15.516
Eh...

12:15.541 --> 12:17.110
Why are you singing right now?

12:17.135 --> 12:19.446
Because I love that song,
and it feels good to sing it.

12:19.471 --> 12:21.741
So you weren't just singing
that to me specifically?

12:21.766 --> 12:23.906
Why would I be singing to you?
You don't even like me.

12:23.908 --> 12:26.657
That's never been officially documented.

12:26.682 --> 12:29.016
Zoey, are you okay? Do you need some...

12:29.041 --> 12:31.696
Ahh! Don't say the word "help."
I'm begging you.

12:33.128 --> 12:35.445
Please, come on in.

12:35.470 --> 12:37.620
Can I get you anything? Water?

12:37.622 --> 12:40.063
Vodka? Xanax?

12:42.210 --> 12:44.212
Okay, maybe I do need help,

12:44.237 --> 12:46.570
because I think I'm going crazy.

12:47.999 --> 12:49.991
Did you want to tell me about it?

12:50.016 --> 12:53.015
People are singing to me, Mo.

12:53.040 --> 12:57.450
An entire neighborhood just
sang a whole Beatles song to me.

12:57.475 --> 12:58.977
Quick question.

12:59.002 --> 13:01.524
Did you recently imbibe
or ingest anything

13:01.549 --> 13:03.298
that came from a "medicinal" type shop?

13:03.323 --> 13:04.958
No. All I know is that, one second,

13:04.983 --> 13:06.361
I'm getting an MRI,
and, the next second...

13:06.385 --> 13:08.119
Complete strangers are
singing John Lennon to you.

13:08.143 --> 13:10.477
Some to me, some to themselves,

13:10.743 --> 13:12.321
almost as if they were singing

13:12.323 --> 13:14.457
what they were all thinking out loud

13:14.482 --> 13:16.860
collectively as a people.

13:17.960 --> 13:19.259
Does that make sense?

13:19.284 --> 13:21.597
No, but I'm an open-minded person.

13:21.599 --> 13:23.448
I'm willing to roll with this.

13:23.914 --> 13:26.980
Maybe you're operating on
a higher plane than the rest of us.

13:27.005 --> 13:29.722
Maybe you're getting a special glimpse
into other people's heads.

13:30.221 --> 13:31.221
If that's the case,

13:31.246 --> 13:32.966
then why aren't you
singing to me right now?

13:33.288 --> 13:35.052
Child, I'm completely baked.

13:35.077 --> 13:37.144
Ain't nothing going on
in my head right now.

13:38.219 --> 13:40.314
You know what? Forget it.

13:40.339 --> 13:42.051
Forget I said any of this.

13:42.053 --> 13:44.181
I shouldn't have told you.
I shouldn't tell anyone.

13:44.206 --> 13:45.454
Keeping my mouth shut from now on,

13:45.456 --> 13:46.581
or else rumors get started,

13:46.606 --> 13:48.276
and then I become the weird music girl

13:48.301 --> 13:49.703
on top of everything else,
and I've got enough problems

13:49.727 --> 13:51.093
without that, thank you very much.

13:51.095 --> 13:53.429
Hey, hey, hey, hey. I am really sorry

13:53.431 --> 13:55.031
that you got so freaked out, okay?

13:55.033 --> 13:57.967
And let me know if it
ever happens again,

13:57.969 --> 13:59.969
because this is the first thing

13:59.971 --> 14:02.612
that I find remotely
interesting about you.

14:07.396 --> 14:12.044
♪ Morning has broken ♪

14:12.069 --> 14:16.239
♪ Like the first morning ♪

14:16.264 --> 14:23.224
♪ Blackbird has spoken
like the first bird ♪

14:24.700 --> 14:26.005
Here we go.

14:26.545 --> 14:27.645
Look at him.

14:27.669 --> 14:29.065
I don't think I've ever been as happy

14:29.067 --> 14:31.403
as that guy is at 9:30 in
the morning on a Tuesday.

14:31.428 --> 14:33.847
He does have a certain
joie de vivre, doesn't he?

14:33.872 --> 14:35.161
Have we ever had joie de vivre?

14:35.186 --> 14:36.917
I don't think we're really
joie de vivre people.

14:36.941 --> 14:39.508
There you guys are.
Joan is in rare form today.

14:39.510 --> 14:41.004
- Come on.
- Wait, wait. What's happening?

14:41.028 --> 14:43.591
You mean she didn't tell you
over Skinnygirl margaritas last night?

14:43.615 --> 14:45.715
Seriously, what is wrong with you?

14:45.717 --> 14:47.082
My mom left me when I was young,

14:47.107 --> 14:48.544
and my whole life has been
a series of rejections

14:48.568 --> 14:51.920
from the opposite sex.
Any other questions?

14:51.945 --> 14:54.746
Yes, I have many, many questions.

14:58.995 --> 15:00.628
_

15:00.653 --> 15:02.098
For those of you who don't know,

15:02.100 --> 15:04.767
we have recently discovered
a bug in the health app

15:04.769 --> 15:06.769
that's supposed to launch in five days

15:06.771 --> 15:08.651
along with the new Sprq Point watch.

15:08.676 --> 15:09.692
What's the bug doing?

15:09.717 --> 15:11.905
It's giving inaccurate readings
of people's blood pressure,

15:11.929 --> 15:13.638
most in the range of 50 over 20.

15:13.663 --> 15:15.588
That's low, isn't it?

15:15.613 --> 15:18.113
Only if should no
longer be living is low.

15:18.138 --> 15:19.982
So, I'm gonna need you guys

15:19.984 --> 15:22.551
to text your friends and
your Adderall dealers

15:22.553 --> 15:24.240
and all the other entitled millennials

15:24.265 --> 15:26.326
you've been chatting with
on Slack and tell them

15:26.351 --> 15:27.982
you're gonna be in for some late nights.

15:28.007 --> 15:29.349
Get to work.

15:34.179 --> 15:36.609
I don't think it's coming from our end.

15:36.634 --> 15:39.168
- Our app code seems fine.
- Must have something to do

15:39.170 --> 15:41.740
with how the watch itself
is recording the data.

15:41.765 --> 15:43.943
I'm gonna clone its firmware repository.

15:43.968 --> 15:46.326
- I can help if you want.
- Thanks, Leif.

15:50.450 --> 15:55.528
♪ All around me are familiar faces ♪

15:55.553 --> 15:58.621
♪ Worn out places ♪

15:58.623 --> 16:02.539
♪ Worn out faces ♪

16:02.564 --> 16:05.998
Leif, do you hear that?

16:06.023 --> 16:07.453
Hear what?

16:07.478 --> 16:12.494
♪ Bright and early for
their daily races ♪

16:12.519 --> 16:15.424
♪ Going nowhere ♪

16:15.449 --> 16:19.809
♪ Going nowhere ♪

16:19.834 --> 16:21.871
You sure you don't hear that?

16:33.511 --> 16:38.213
♪ Their tears are filling
up their glasses ♪

16:38.238 --> 16:40.973
♪ No expression ♪

16:40.998 --> 16:44.644
♪ No expression ♪

16:44.681 --> 16:49.515
♪ Hide my head,
I want to drown my sorrow ♪

16:49.540 --> 16:52.355
♪ No tomorrow ♪

16:52.380 --> 16:55.621
♪ No tomorrow ♪

16:56.105 --> 16:59.014
♪ And I find it kinda funny ♪

16:59.016 --> 17:02.113
♪ I find it kinda sad ♪

17:02.138 --> 17:07.934
♪ The dreams in which I'm dying
are the best I ever had ♪

17:07.959 --> 17:10.777
♪ I find it hard to tell you ♪

17:10.801 --> 17:13.506
♪ I find it hard to take ♪

17:13.531 --> 17:19.246
♪ When people run in circles,
it's a very, very ♪

17:19.853 --> 17:24.277
♪ Mad world ♪

17:28.069 --> 17:31.918
♪ Mad world ♪

17:48.963 --> 17:52.949
Come on, people!
Let's party like it's 1978!

18:00.606 --> 18:02.206
You actually came to my gig.

18:02.208 --> 18:04.035
You told me to tell
you if happens again.

18:04.060 --> 18:05.144
All day, nothing, and then,

18:05.169 --> 18:08.252
out of nowhere, it happened again.

18:08.277 --> 18:09.988
What now? A bunch of cartoon birds

18:10.013 --> 18:12.093
land on your shoulders and
sing show tunes to you?

18:12.118 --> 18:13.933
No, this was just one person

18:13.958 --> 18:17.131
singing something so raw
and painful and personal,

18:17.156 --> 18:19.494
I almost felt embarrassed
listening to it.

18:19.519 --> 18:20.891
What do you think that means?

18:20.893 --> 18:22.363
One of two things,

18:22.388 --> 18:24.205
either your powers are getting stronger,

18:24.230 --> 18:27.666
honing on specific targets,
or you're losing it,

18:27.691 --> 18:29.496
in which case, I will do my civic duty

18:29.521 --> 18:31.445
and drive you to the nearest
mental health clinic

18:31.470 --> 18:34.330
as soon as I'm finished making
seventies night my bitch.

18:34.355 --> 18:36.332
I am just very, very confused.

18:36.357 --> 18:39.186
You said that I was getting a glimpse
into other people's heads.

18:39.211 --> 18:41.278
I said maybe you were,
and you should really take

18:41.280 --> 18:43.145
everything I say when I'm
high with a grain of salt.

18:43.169 --> 18:44.325
But it just doesn't make sense.

18:44.349 --> 18:46.794
The guy who was singing
is handsome and happy

18:46.819 --> 18:50.080
and charming and very, very sexy,

18:50.105 --> 18:52.082
and, if your theory is correct,

18:52.107 --> 18:54.674
then he should only be singing,
like, massively upbeat anthems

18:54.699 --> 18:56.466
about how totally awesome he is.

18:56.491 --> 18:59.098
Well, maybe he's not quite
as awesome as you think he is.

18:59.123 --> 19:00.588
What was he singing?

19:00.613 --> 19:02.551
I think it's called "Mad World."

19:02.576 --> 19:05.776
Mm. Your boy is hurting.
That song is real dark.

19:05.801 --> 19:07.938
Look, songs are all just an expression

19:07.940 --> 19:09.754
of our deepest wants and desires...

19:09.779 --> 19:14.816
Joy, pain, heartbreak,
yearning, forgiveness, revenge.

19:14.841 --> 19:16.507
Good music can make you feel things

19:16.532 --> 19:18.176
you can't express in words.

19:18.201 --> 19:22.163
So, if I do have this... power,

19:22.188 --> 19:24.035
maybe Simon really is hurting.

19:24.060 --> 19:26.387
And the song that he sang only to you

19:26.412 --> 19:28.512
might have been his cry for help.

19:28.537 --> 19:29.537
Hmm?

19:32.447 --> 19:35.840
_

19:44.652 --> 19:47.277
I can't find anything.

19:47.279 --> 19:49.471
No memory leak,
no out-of-bounds exception,

19:49.496 --> 19:51.191
not even a floating-point error.

19:51.216 --> 19:53.317
Hey, uh, not that I'm
keeping tabs or anything,

19:53.342 --> 19:55.408
but that's like your
fourth cup of coffee today.

19:55.454 --> 19:57.020
How late were you here last night?

19:57.022 --> 19:58.285
Oh, I wasn't just here.

19:58.310 --> 20:00.901
I went to this club
called The Make Out Place.

20:00.926 --> 20:03.246
You went to a club?

20:03.271 --> 20:04.905
I'll be right back.

20:04.930 --> 20:06.512
Okay.

20:06.832 --> 20:08.957
Club. What's next, Burning Man?

20:25.184 --> 20:26.902
What are you leaning towards?

20:27.871 --> 20:30.127
Tough call. Middle of the day.

20:30.152 --> 20:32.324
Do I get a sugar cereal
that'll make me crash hard

20:32.349 --> 20:34.502
or something super healthy
that I'll totally hate?

20:34.527 --> 20:36.644
These are the struggles.

20:37.079 --> 20:40.174
My dad's a huge fa...
Well, was a huge fan of granola.

20:40.199 --> 20:42.441
I think I'm gonna go that route.

20:42.466 --> 20:44.441
It's kinda the best of
both worlds scenario.

20:44.996 --> 20:46.558
What made your dad turn on granola?

20:46.583 --> 20:47.645
Did granola hurt him in some way?

20:47.669 --> 20:49.371
Rob his house? Make out with his lady?

20:49.396 --> 20:52.308
No. He just, uh, can't really swallow

20:52.333 --> 20:53.707
anymore, because he's dying.

20:53.732 --> 20:55.690
Well, slowly dying of this
rare neurological disease,

20:55.714 --> 20:58.315
and each week, he, like,
loses another ability,

20:58.340 --> 20:59.817
therefore, big chunks of granola

20:59.819 --> 21:01.683
would just cause him to choke.

21:01.708 --> 21:06.010
So, that's a whole lot of
TMI I just spewed at you.

21:06.035 --> 21:07.424
I-I'm sorry. I had no idea.

21:07.426 --> 21:08.505
Why would you? We're strangers.

21:08.529 --> 21:09.606
There's no way you could know that,

21:09.630 --> 21:10.966
just like there's no way I could know

21:10.990 --> 21:12.973
if you were secretly
miserable or something.

21:12.998 --> 21:15.213
I mean, you seem happy, but who knows

21:15.238 --> 21:18.915
what other people
are really thinking, right?

21:18.940 --> 21:21.478
Anyway, I'm Zoey.
I don't know if you know that,

21:21.503 --> 21:23.818
and, if you want to forget
this entire interaction

21:23.843 --> 21:26.335
ever happened, totally get it.

21:26.360 --> 21:27.593
Zoey...

21:29.775 --> 21:31.348
we can do better than cereal.

21:31.350 --> 21:32.697
You wanna take a walk?

21:33.204 --> 21:34.662
Yeah.

21:34.687 --> 21:36.720
You were right.

21:36.722 --> 21:39.323
This was the best
cheesecake I've ever had.

21:39.325 --> 21:41.126
Uh-uh, cheesequake.

21:41.151 --> 21:44.071
- Cheesequake.
- Ah.

21:44.096 --> 21:46.707
Still, isn't it in
bad taste for a bakery

21:46.732 --> 21:48.799
to capitalize off natural disasters

21:48.801 --> 21:50.462
with a moderately clever pun?

21:50.487 --> 21:51.679
Oh, definitely in bad taste,

21:51.704 --> 21:53.798
but, when they're as
good as these were...

21:53.823 --> 21:56.220
Unh... do we really care?

21:56.948 --> 21:59.111
- No.
- Hmm.

22:01.702 --> 22:04.291
So, are you usually that honest

22:04.316 --> 22:06.579
about your dad and his condition?

22:06.604 --> 22:09.681
Not so much. I've found, in general,

22:09.706 --> 22:12.445
death and dying tend not to be
the best conversation starters.

22:12.470 --> 22:14.958
Still, are you angry?
Are you crying all the time?

22:14.960 --> 22:16.797
What's that whole process like for you?

22:16.822 --> 22:18.283
Why are you asking?

22:19.041 --> 22:21.119
Is one of your parents dying, too?

22:21.144 --> 22:22.861
It's nothing to be ashamed of.

22:28.142 --> 22:29.173
If I show you something,

22:29.198 --> 22:31.236
can you promise to keep
it only between us?

22:37.108 --> 22:41.922
This is a photo of my dad
and I when I was a kid.

22:41.947 --> 22:44.329
I've been carrying it
everywhere I go lately.

22:45.302 --> 22:48.587
And you don't want others to
know about this, because...

22:48.612 --> 22:51.361
He killed himself, Zoey.

22:52.288 --> 22:53.986
Five months ago.

22:54.011 --> 22:55.743
Looking at this photo

22:55.768 --> 22:57.534
is the only thing that
makes me feel better.

23:00.380 --> 23:04.003
And I know what you're
going through sucks, but it's...

23:05.297 --> 23:07.264
it's way worse when they're gone.

23:07.547 --> 23:10.086
I mean, your dad's still here.
You gotta take advantage of that.

23:10.111 --> 23:11.748
Talk to him.

23:11.750 --> 23:14.037
Hold his hand. Do things with him.

23:14.062 --> 23:16.396
'Cause, when he's gone, well, it's...

23:18.904 --> 23:23.283
Uh, this is the only thing
that I could hold on to.

23:25.413 --> 23:27.329
I'm so sorry.

23:30.603 --> 23:33.047
Are you talking to anyone about this?

23:33.525 --> 23:35.564
Other than you? No.

23:36.299 --> 23:39.219
I've become a real expert at
bottling my shame and pain

23:39.244 --> 23:41.431
and hiding it from the world.

23:42.858 --> 23:44.366
Listen,

23:44.391 --> 23:49.063
I'm not an expert on this or anything,

23:49.088 --> 23:51.343
but you can't just keep it in.

23:55.123 --> 23:59.306
We live in a very,
very mad world, Simon,

23:59.331 --> 24:02.032
but if you open up and express
what you're feeling to others,

24:02.034 --> 24:05.335
well, I mean, it's gotta be better

24:05.337 --> 24:07.022
than what you're doing now.

24:07.921 --> 24:09.640
Living your whole life in your head,

24:09.665 --> 24:13.859
like this prison
my dad's now in, that's...

24:15.026 --> 24:16.351
... torture.

24:18.523 --> 24:20.342
You're amazing.

24:20.367 --> 24:23.382
It's like you know exactly
what's going on inside my brain.

24:26.602 --> 24:29.104
It's a real miracle
we found each other, Zoey.

24:30.060 --> 24:31.760
Yeah.

24:32.496 --> 24:34.736
Such a miracle.

24:38.557 --> 24:41.446
These are all the pills Dad's taking?

24:41.471 --> 24:43.337
Yes. I had to make a spreadsheet

24:43.362 --> 24:45.666
just to keep track,
which pill, which hour.

24:45.691 --> 24:49.518
I-I could do a whole PowerPoint
presentation on this right now.

24:49.543 --> 24:51.494
You would be very impressed.

24:51.519 --> 24:54.150
I'm just impressed
you know the term "PowerPoint."

24:54.175 --> 24:55.924
Well, what do they all do?

24:55.949 --> 24:59.186
Um, okay, well,
this one helped me sleep.

24:59.211 --> 25:01.127
This one made me forget all my problems

25:01.152 --> 25:02.588
for about five hours,

25:02.613 --> 25:03.628
- and this one...
- Mom, you've tried them?

25:03.652 --> 25:06.011
No. Yes. Some of them.

25:07.317 --> 25:09.510
That is so unlike you.

25:09.535 --> 25:11.702
I know. I just...

25:11.786 --> 25:14.400
I wanted to feel what
your dad was feeling.

25:14.425 --> 25:16.058
That's all.

25:17.308 --> 25:19.955
So, what is new with you?

25:19.980 --> 25:23.041
Oh, nothing much.

25:23.380 --> 25:25.721
Well, I left the office
in the middle of a crisis

25:25.746 --> 25:29.881
to spend time with this coworker
I have a massive crush on.

25:30.301 --> 25:31.721
Then I used information

25:31.746 --> 25:33.299
I shouldn't have even known about him

25:33.324 --> 25:37.250
to form this bond like some
sort of adorable psycho.

25:37.275 --> 25:39.385
That is so unlike you.

25:39.410 --> 25:42.291
I just haven't been myself lately,

25:42.899 --> 25:47.061
and I'm worried about you
and Dad all the time, and...

25:50.094 --> 25:51.720
What?

25:51.745 --> 25:53.330
What did I say?

25:57.746 --> 26:00.885
No, nothing. It's not you.

26:00.910 --> 26:02.666
This is all just...

26:04.195 --> 26:06.166
very overwhelming.

26:07.980 --> 26:11.174
I mean, six months ago, Dad was...

26:11.573 --> 26:13.025
he was okay.

26:13.050 --> 26:15.502
You know, we could still
communicate with each other,

26:15.527 --> 26:19.065
and now I don't know what's
going on in his head,

26:19.090 --> 26:22.643
how much he's processing,
if he's processing.

26:23.612 --> 26:25.946
I should have been the
one this happened to.

26:25.971 --> 26:28.346
- Don't say that.
- No, it is true.

26:28.371 --> 26:30.174
I mean, your dad was
always better than me

26:30.199 --> 26:33.104
at handling emergencies, all the...

26:33.970 --> 26:36.471
emotional stuff, and we all know it.

26:36.496 --> 26:38.830
Okay, if that's the case,

26:38.855 --> 26:44.174
then maybe we should ask him how
to handle our current situation.

26:52.255 --> 26:56.090
I think we're just gonna have
to stumble through it together.

26:56.303 --> 26:58.096
The blind leading the blind.

26:58.121 --> 27:00.910
- Jinx.
- No take-backs.

27:06.214 --> 27:08.949
If you had the power to
know what was going on

27:08.974 --> 27:13.877
in other people's heads,
do you think you'd feel guilty?

27:14.417 --> 27:17.347
No, I think I'd just get
my feelings hurt a lot more often.

27:17.372 --> 27:20.006
There she is, my favorite mind-reader.

27:21.408 --> 27:23.349
That's me...

27:23.374 --> 27:25.007
Zo-stradamus.

27:25.032 --> 27:28.136
I just wanted to say thank you
again for our talk yesterday,

27:28.161 --> 27:30.361
and I'm here for you, too,

27:30.386 --> 27:32.246
if you ever need someone to lean on.

27:32.271 --> 27:34.441
- I mean that.
- Great. Sounds good.

27:34.466 --> 27:35.910
Will definitely take you up on that.

27:35.935 --> 27:37.761
You know what?
I forgot a pencil at my desk,

27:37.786 --> 27:40.261
- so I have to excuse myself.
- Just one...

27:41.126 --> 27:43.636
Uh, mind blown.

27:43.661 --> 27:44.964
So many questions.

27:44.989 --> 27:46.355
How did that happen? What?

27:46.380 --> 27:48.699
And did you really make
contact without telling me?

27:48.724 --> 27:51.722
We might have bonded on a deep,
emotional level.

27:51.747 --> 27:54.105
Zoey, got a minute?

27:54.130 --> 27:55.527
Mm-hmm.

27:58.308 --> 27:59.371
Hi, Joan.

27:59.396 --> 28:01.012
I'm going to be
uncharacteristically honest

28:01.036 --> 28:02.598
with you right now.
Don't get used to it.

28:02.622 --> 28:04.156
You're one of the best
programmers we have,

28:04.180 --> 28:06.769
which is why it's between you
and one other person for this job.

28:06.794 --> 28:09.230
- It is? That's...
- Meaningless, unless I pick you.

28:09.255 --> 28:11.021
This is a big opportunity.

28:11.046 --> 28:12.412
Why did you leave work yesterday,

28:12.437 --> 28:14.613
and why are you so
distracted all of a sudden?

28:14.638 --> 28:17.231
- You noticed that?
- I notice everything.

28:17.415 --> 28:18.818
Maybe you don't want this promotion.

28:18.842 --> 28:21.208
No. Uh, I just have a lot going on.

28:21.233 --> 28:23.044
That wasn't me looking for an answer.

28:23.069 --> 28:26.356
That was me telling you to get
back to your desk and focus.

28:26.381 --> 28:27.647
Okay.

28:28.953 --> 28:32.247
Hey. So what was that all about?

28:32.272 --> 28:33.272
Nothing. She was just...

28:33.297 --> 28:34.662
Was she giving you a clue about the bug?

28:34.686 --> 28:35.897
Does it have to do with our software

28:35.921 --> 28:37.822
or the watch's firmware?
At least tell us that much.

28:37.846 --> 28:39.740
- She didn't say anything.
- Are you sure? 'Cause it kinda

28:39.764 --> 28:42.044
seemed like she was giving
you some inside information.

28:42.069 --> 28:43.491
You know what I mean? Leaning in,

28:43.516 --> 28:45.013
breaking the glass ceiling.

28:45.038 --> 28:46.671
A woman's place is in the house...

28:46.696 --> 28:48.013
and the Senate. What up?

28:48.038 --> 28:49.459
Okay, dude, come on.
You gotta stop trying

28:49.483 --> 28:51.848
to turn this into, like,
an us-versus-her thing.

28:51.873 --> 28:53.253
Okay? We're all in this together.

28:53.278 --> 28:54.895
Fine.

28:54.920 --> 28:57.154
Look, so, Zoey, no matter what happened,

28:57.179 --> 29:00.356
whether Joan gave you some sort
of special advantage or not,

29:00.381 --> 29:01.653
you should know that...

29:01.678 --> 29:04.497
♪ All I do is win, win,
win, no matter what ♪

29:04.522 --> 29:06.107
♪ Got money on mind ♪

29:06.131 --> 29:07.731
♪ I can never get enough ♪

29:07.756 --> 29:10.356
♪ And every time
I step up in the building ♪

29:10.381 --> 29:12.966
♪ Everybody's hands go up ♪

29:15.513 --> 29:16.872
♪ And they stay there ♪

29:16.897 --> 29:18.348
- ♪ Yeah ♪
- ♪ And they say yeah ♪

29:18.373 --> 29:19.693
- ♪ What? ♪
- ♪ And they stay there ♪

29:19.717 --> 29:22.239
♪ Up, down, up, down, up, down ♪

29:22.264 --> 29:25.348
♪ 'Cause all I do is win, win, win ♪

29:25.373 --> 29:28.419
♪ And if you're goin' in,
put your hands in the air ♪

29:28.444 --> 29:30.286
♪ Make 'em stay there ♪

29:33.458 --> 29:35.610
Oh, good. A dance break.

29:35.635 --> 29:36.834
♪ Hunh ♪

29:42.756 --> 29:47.526
♪ Ey, ey, ey, ey, ey, ey ♪

29:49.993 --> 29:52.747
I so wish I could tell HR about this.

29:54.220 --> 29:57.132
♪ All I do is win, win,
win, no matter what ♪

29:57.157 --> 29:58.888
- ♪ Ey ♪
- ♪ Got money on my mind ♪

29:58.913 --> 30:00.700
- ♪ I can never get enough ♪
- ♪ Ey ♪

30:00.725 --> 30:03.177
♪ And every time
I step up in the building ♪

30:03.202 --> 30:05.636
♪ Everybody's hands go up ♪

30:10.058 --> 30:13.751
I'm sorry. Whether she gave me
some advantage or not, what?

30:13.776 --> 30:16.443
I'm rooting for you. That's all.

30:16.681 --> 30:18.709
Glad to hear it.

30:18.711 --> 30:19.977
Yeah.

30:24.813 --> 30:26.899
Two cheesequakes, please.

30:29.507 --> 30:30.843
Thank you.

30:32.877 --> 30:34.343
Back so soon?

30:34.368 --> 30:36.352
I warned you.
Those things are addictive.

30:36.377 --> 30:39.912
Hi. I was just about to call you.

30:39.937 --> 30:41.211
Is everything okay?

30:42.186 --> 30:43.352
Not really.

30:43.377 --> 30:45.469
I was hoping I could take you up

30:45.494 --> 30:48.727
on that whole leaning
on each other thing.

30:48.752 --> 30:50.548
Is right now a bad time?

30:50.573 --> 30:53.461
Babe, there you are.

30:54.488 --> 30:55.696
I hope you're stopping him

30:55.721 --> 30:57.789
from buying any more of those things.

30:58.257 --> 30:59.736
He's so obsessed. He wants them to be

30:59.760 --> 31:01.891
one of the dessert
options at the wedding.

31:02.368 --> 31:05.391
The wedding?

31:05.416 --> 31:07.909
- This is my fiancée, Jessica.
- Hi.

31:07.934 --> 31:09.868
Uh, Zoey and I work with
each other at Sprq Point.

31:09.892 --> 31:12.633
- Oh.
- Not exactly work with each other.

